        <descriptionSet>
            <description>Hugely popular in schools and homes from the 1880s through the 1920s, stereoscopes were viewed with a hand-held viewer. By combining two nearly-identical images the experience mimicked a 3-d reality.  One guide noted “The making of stereoscopic pictures is one of the most lucrative departments of photography, and the number and variety of subjects everywhere…make a collection of endless extent and beauty." Underwood &amp;amp Underwood produced over 3 million stereocards in 40 years. 
</description>
